# {{PROJECT_NAME}} — QA standard (the QA-twin discipline)

The **QA twin** is an autonomous, per-lane quality discipline: a digital stand-in
for the operator's own checking, testing, validation, and fixing. It runs against
the **LIVE running system**, cross-checks every surface against its source of
truth, runs behavioral scenarios, fixes what it safely can (review-gated) or
routes gaps onward, and emits a phone-friendly report card.

This standard is the **discipline**; `{{CMD_PREFIX}}-qa`
(`03-templates/agent-commands/core/qa/`) is the **command scaffold** that runs it.
The pattern is inherited by every brain from the hub; the **harness is
per-lane** and product-scoped — each lane instantiates its own surfaces,
source-of-truth endpoints, and scenarios and does **not** inherit another lane's
harness.

> **Provenance.** This discipline is the generalized form of the Northwind System
> QA twin (`xs-qa`), promoted into the Brain Factory hub as a reusable primitive.
> The Northwind `xs-qa` harness itself stays product-scoped in the Northwind brain;
> only the pattern, stages, cadence, taxonomy, and lessons below are inherited.

## Stages (the pipeline)

Run in order. `fast` runs stages 1–3, 5, 6; `deep` adds stage 4.

1. **MAP — the oracle.** Refresh the surface map: every page/view/lane/route, its
   feeding source of truth, expected content, and every control classified
   **MUTATING vs SAFE**. Cache it; refresh when the product changed.
2. **EXERCISE (sweep).** For every surface, on the LIVE system: capture the
   rendered output, extract displayed data, inventory controls (+ disabled
   state), click-test only SAFE controls and confirm a real state change, capture
   console/network/log errors. Sweep desktop **and** mobile/touch viewports.
3. **VALIDATE (displayed-vs-source-of-truth).** Per surface: read the rendered
   output (what the user sees) + the source data (ground truth) and judge
   data-correct, render-ok, controls-ok. Report only real issues, each with
   source-value-vs-displayed-value evidence.
4. **BEHAVIORAL (deep gear).** Run the scenario matrix (backup → permute →
   restore for state-mutating ones). Assert *eligible + reachable + ≥1 expected
   effect within N, else the precise blocker* — a snapshot cannot prove behavior
   over time. Instantiate for this lane: does-the-action-happen per actor/lane;
   teardown/clearing; config-propagation; isolation/no-leak; rehydrate; freshness;
   orchestrator-health.
5. **REPORT (phone-friendly).** A visual report card: surface thumbnails
   (🟢/🟡/🔴), a one-liner per failure with evidence, behavioral results, what was
   auto-fixed + PR'd, and the 1–2 things that need the operator. Lead with a
   one-line summary; push it so it reaches the operator when away.
6. **ACT (fix-route).** Route every finding FIX / IMPROVE / FLAG (below),
   max-autonomous up to the one review-gate.

## Cadence

- **After every deploy →** `fast`, then push the report card (the final deploy
  step).
- **Nightly →** `deep` (the behavioral matrix); wire into the scheduler.
- Always **runtime-verify** deployed fixes — green CI alone has shipped a
  mechanism that never moved the rendered value.

## Fix-route taxonomy

Every finding routes exactly one of three ways:

- **FIX** — a clear bug. Understand → implement on a branch (no live config) →
  **adversarial review** (understand→fix→review→verify) → PR (CI-gated).
  Auto-merge only green, low-risk fixes; **HOLD** judgment calls for the operator.
  The review-gate is the one guardrail — never auto-merge what it flags.
- **IMPROVE / EXTEND** — ugly, cramped, or missing, but not a bug. Route to the
  lane's design/UX path with the design system.
- **FLAG** — redesigns, behavioral judgment calls, or anything risky. Surface on
  the report card for the operator to decide.

## Non-negotiable lessons

Each was learned the hard way; violating one produces a **wrong verdict**. They
are generalized from the donor `xs-qa` twin — the parentheticals name the
original product-specific failure so the reasoning is preserved.

1. **Test the LIVE running system, not the repo checkout.** Config, live data,
   and derived state live on the running instance; a read of the repo *template*
   yields wrong, config-dependent conclusions. Treat any config-dependent claim
   from a repo read as unverified.
2. **Let the system settle after boot/deploy before trusting time-sensitive
   readings.** A fresh-boot loading flash misreads (e.g. a metric that
   self-corrects once background fetches finish). Poll health UP, then wait a
   cycle before trusting time/rate/aggregate values.
3. **Judge from the rendered output + the source, not the raw markup string.**
   Client source (e.g. a template/`text/babel` payload) can contain
   bug-referencing comments and unrendered values → substring matches are false
   positives. Read the rendered screenshot/response; cross-check against the
   source data.
4. **"Renders" ≠ "correct."** Always cross-check displayed-vs-source-of-truth:
   numbers, counts, signs, units/currency, labels. A surface can render cleanly
   and still show a stale or wrong value.
5. **Never fire mutating/destructive controls on the live system**
   (Stop/Pause/Close/Run/Save/Add/Remove/Enable). Inventory them and confirm
   enabled/disabled state; click-test only SAFE controls (toggles, tab/view
   switches, filters, popovers) and verify a real state change.
6. **State-mutating scenarios: backup → permute → restore.** Back up config/state
   before a permutation and restore after, with encoding-safe writes (e.g.
   UTF-8-no-BOM). Never stage or commit live config.
7. **A setting must ROUND-TRIP + PROPAGATE — "saved (200 OK)" ≠ "applied."** A
   control can POST cleanly yet be silently dropped (a schema that ignores the
   field → the engine keeps the default forever). For each setting, assert it
   (a) round-trips via a read-back, (b) persists to storage, (c) reaches the
   consumer/engine, and (d) shows identically on every surface. A key **absent**
   from the read-back after a save is a FAILURE, not a pass.
8. **"What's MISSING" is a finding — a correctness check cannot see an absent
   feature.** Run a completeness pass against an expected-feature checklist and
   flag anything present-in-spec but absent-in-UI.
9. **A changed client asset must be cache-busted/versioned or the fix never
   reaches the user.** A deployed asset served from cache with a stale version
   marker is invisible. "Asset changed in the diff, no version/cache-bust bump"
   is a blocking defect.
10. **Frozen/installed/deployed paths diverge from the repo.** In a packaged app,
    roots and log/config paths differ from the repo layout. A "reads/writes path
    X" fix must be verified against where the RUNNING system actually resolves the
    path (a box-probe), not the repo assumption.
11. **Deployed + byte-confirmed ≠ renders-correct for the user.** A fix can be on
    the box (right file, right version) and still be wrong on screen: (a) a stale
    browser/PWA cache serves the old output — the operator's phone is the prime
    stale-cache surface, so verify uncached/hard-reloaded and assert assets send
    revalidation headers; (b) correct client gates fed a wrong server signal still
    render wrong. Verify the fix moved the RENDERED value on the real surface and
    on a mobile viewport, and re-verify across all views and lanes — a partially
    ported fix is the recurring failure.

## Instantiation checklist (per lane)

- [ ] Point `{{CMD_PREFIX}}-qa` at this lane's live surfaces and source-of-truth
      endpoints.
- [ ] Build the harness under an app-repo `scripts/qa/` (map, sweep, validate,
      scenarios, report-card) — do not reuse another lane's harness.
- [ ] Enumerate this lane's MUTATING vs SAFE controls in the surface map.
- [ ] Instantiate the behavioral scenarios that matter for this product.
- [ ] Wire `fast` into every deploy and `deep` into the nightly scheduler.
- [ ] Keep the surface map and scenario matrix living — extend as the product grows.
